2.0 of 5 bubbles
Beautiful scenery but dismaying amount of rubbish!!!!
We did a 3d2n cruise which was good and have reviewed that elsewhere.

Halong Bay itself is breathtaking in its beauty and I simply loved cruising around the bay and took oodles of photos.
However, I was simply horrified at the amount of floating rubbish. This is a UNESCO site for heavens sake!! I think the staff of the many many cruising boats could help pick out this rubbish. I collected some when kayaking.
It really really upset me. It's so unnecessary and utterly spoils an international heritage site that should be preserved for all.
More needs to be done to deal with the issue of rubbish in the bay. The Vietnamese Govt need to address this issue before it's too late.....
Written May 31, 2016
Julie R
Newton Abbot, UK11 contributions
Polluted and ruined
Apr 2016 ‚Ä¢ Couples
We were really looking forward to this over night cruise, unfortunately misty weather so visibility poor but could see how beautiful the views would be in better weather and this is no reason for our rating. We were encouraged to swim from back of boat which only two of us did. It appeared clear water at the time. PLEASE DO NOT DO THIS. later on during early evening we were squid fishing and could not believe the amount of sewerage and rubbish pouring into the water from all the boats. Absolutely disgusting I am surprised we did not come down with dysentery. You have this wonderful site but as soon as you look down at the water it makes you feel sick at the garbage floating past. unacceptable when the boat companies are making so much money from tourists that they don't clean up their act.
This completely took away from what should have been a great trip there was good food on board comfortable cabin and the cave visit was amazing.
The boat staff should not allow anyone to swim in this water.
Written April 24, 2016
Peter C
Narrabri, New South Wales, Australia20 contributions
3.0 of 5 bubbles
We are destroying it!!
Before I went on the tour I had heard mixed stories, but mainly it was amazing ' you have to see it'.
Unfortunately that is not the case, in actual fact the tourism industry is destroying this once natural beauty. Pollution is clearly scattered across the bay, plastics, oil slicks from almost every boat. The water is nearly as busy as Hanoi itself with approx 600 boats operating in the area.
The tours on the islands themselves are again destroying the natural environment. Cigarette butts and more litter all around, in the bushes or anywhere else for that matter. I seen some of the staff myself litter. Then the people who want the perfect selfie in the limestone caves stepping over the boundary lines and trampling on top of everything.
Something has to be done about it, but sadly I doubt anything will.
My partner and I felt kind of bad after visiting, and that's not how one should feel after seeing a sight like that.
Thousands of tourists a day visit the place, mega bucks for someone. And that someone needs to spend some of that money on preservation!!!
Written April 16, 2016
tati-mar
Malm√∂, Sweden48 contributions
Heartbreaking due to pollution!
Apr 2016 ‚Ä¢ Family
We went on 1 night boat tour of Ha Long Bay. It's easy to see why this was named a wonder of the world and it is absolutely stunning (one of the most amazing natural beauties I've seen) IF you can install a filter from all the rubbish and pollution around you. To be honest I was heartbroken to see what state Ha Long bay is in. I will not exaggerate if I say that it was at times impossible to find a patch of clean water and fresh air. The level of pollution around is staggering. Tons of plastic in the water, smell of fuel in the air because you are constantly surrounded by about a hundred other boats. Our captain said that there are 600 boats leaving each day just from that harbour, many staying overnight running generators for the power/air con and therefore constantly adding pollution. I felt bad because I was contributing to this by being on that boat overnight. I couldn't enjoy it due to all above and wouldn't do it again. I will also write a letter to the ministry of tourism of Vietnam and Unesco asking them to take action to protect Ha Long Bay for the future generations.
Written April 13, 2016
ferenza
Bussum, The Netherlands2 contributions
Aloha Halong Bay Boattrip is terrible!!
Mar 2016 ‚Ä¢ Friends
There were a lot of promises made, but almost none of them actually happened. One of them was going to the caves.
The first day we were told we couldn't go to the caves, but we could go the next day.
So the first day we almost didn't do anything, except kanooying for 30 minutes. Also, we only sailed for an hour the first day, and then stayed by the peer, doing nothing. We had to wait all the time and there was no one to answer our questions.
Next morning we had to wake up at 6 am (one hour earlier than scheduled) because then it was sure we could go to the caves. After breakfast at 7 am, we had to wait for 3 hours on the (cold) deck, before we finally left the peer and headed to the caves. When we arrived by the entrance of the caves, we were told we couldn't go and we had to go back to the boat. We were promised a 50 percent refund, because we by far didn't get what we paid for. Of course we didn't get the full refund, but only 10 dollars, while we paid 75 dollars.
At night the heating system didn't work and the beds were as hard as wood with only a really thin sheet. It was absolutely freezing! Also, the bathrooms were really dirty.
The cooking classes that were promised were really bad and while we were with 15 people, we only had 3 plates to cook with.
Halong Bay is beautiful, but make sure you choose the right company to do the trip with! Don't choose Aloha!!
